==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tram
<hw>Tram</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prov. E. <ets>tram</ets>
a coal wagon, the shaft of a cart or carriage, a beam or bar; probably
of Scand, origin; cf. OSw. <ets>tr⟦aring⟧m</ets>, <ets>trum</ets>, a
beam, OD. <ets>drom</ets>, Prov. & OHG. <ets>tram</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A four-wheeled truck running on rails, and used in a
mine, as for carrying coal or ore.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The shaft of a cart.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>De Quincey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One of the rails of a tramway.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A car on a horse railroad.</def>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Tram car</b></col>, <cd>a car made to run on a tramway,
especially a street railway car.</cd> -- <col><b>Tram plate</b></col>,
<cd>a flat piece of iron laid down as a rail.</cd> -- <col><b>Tram
pot</b></col> <fld>(Milling)</fld>, <cd>the step and support for the
lower end of the spindle of a millstone.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tram</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tram
<hw>Tram</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>trama</ets> weft, or F.
<ets>trame</ets>.]</ety> <def>A silk thread formed of two or more
threads twisted together, used especially for the weft, or cross
threads, of the best quality of velvets and silk goods.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tram</ent>⟦br⟧

